{
  "texts": [
    "While forming a local energy market, it is valuable to select participants that complement each other's net load curves.",
    "For example, a building that has a net load at a certain time would benefit from being in a market with a net generator at that time.",
    "The complementarity of market participants is essentially a measure of how well the electricity generation and demand curves match up.",
    "There have been game theoretic approaches to evaluating complementary participants, and the authors in Agwan et al. (2021) have developed a complementarity metric that uses net generation and load curves to evaluate the marginal value of adding new participants to the local energy markets.",
    "Once a market has been set up, we need to facilitate energy trades between participants."
  ]
}